commitResults.messageBody:
For each contact, we would like to assign common statuses to help
the user track how far into the sales funnel the person has reached.
4 types of lead statuses have been identified.

Let's restrict the user's ability to choose the lead status of each
contact to four choices, to ensure that the descriptors are consistent
and categorisable.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix GUI elements for lead statuses
Add skeletal classes for Transactions feature
Add support for Transactions in Model and AddressBook.
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, AddressBook stores data for Persons only. To manage
Transactions and the relationships between Persons and Transactions,
the data for Transactions and relations should be stored in
AddressBook as well.

Let's add a list of transactions (UniqueTransactionList) and relations
(PersonTransactionMap) to AddressBook attributes, and the skeletal
methods to support the operations of these attributes.

Let's also add abstract methods to the Model to support the operations
on these attributes, and skeletal code to the ModelManager to facilitate
the implementations of these operations.

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove lead status search from StatusCommmand.
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously, the status command was to support searching by status
categories. However, this would be the first deviation from the 'find'
command, and filtering would be done in a within the 'status' command.

Let's remove the searching from StatusCommand, and leave the
implementation of search by lead status to the FindCommand.
StatusCommand is now strictly for the setting of lead statuses of
contacts.

commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, lead statuses do not have a storage format, and all
statuses of contacts are reset to Uncontacted every time the app runs.

Let's add storage for lead statuses to store the newly set status
of each Person. This way, the app will reflect the updated lead status
each time it runs.

Currently, lead statuses only save the status names of the contacts'
lead status. To allow the user to be able to track when they last
updated the status of a contact (GitHub Issues #62), a new timestamp
feature for lead statuses has been implemented, as a java Instant.

Let's have the Instant of a newly set lead status to be set when the
LeadStatus object is instantiated. Previously, the implementation of
StatusCommand prevents the user from executing the command if the lead
status is the same as the current one. This means that the LeadStatus
will never be created. With this new implementation of timestamps, we
can also ensure that a user cannot refresh the timestamp of a lead
status if their status does not change.

However, this implementation does not stop a user from changing the
status to a new status and changing it back, to refresh the timestamp.
Through my research on other CRMs, this seems like an expected
behaviour anyway. Ideally, a log of the changes to statuses done by the
user should be implemented to reflect their actions.
